Challenge 1 — Summarize each group
Get each group’s average change and its spread (standard deviation). Fill in the grouping column and the column you’re averaging.












The column that says which group a sheep is in is trmt. You want the average of change.



sheep |&gt;
  group_by(trmt) |&gt;
  summarise(avg = mean(change), spread = sd(change))
sheep |&gt;
  group_by(trmt) |&gt;
  summarise(avg = mean(change), spread = sd(change))

Challenge 5 — Be a skeptic: the median difference
The mean can be pulled around by one odd sheep, so a careful skeptic also looks at the median. As a first step, calculate the observed median difference between the groups. (The full robustness check shuffles the labels too, see the optional cell below.) Fill in the statistic name.












It looks just like "diff in means", but with medians.



sheep |&gt;
  specify(change ~ trmt) |&gt;
  calculate(stat = "diff in medians", order = c("esc", "ctrl"))
sheep |&gt;
  specify(change ~ trmt) |&gt;
  calculate(stat = "diff in medians", order = c("esc", "ctrl"))











NoteOptional: the full robustness check (not graded)



The exercise above computes the observed median difference. The complete check also shuffles the labels 1000 times and counts how often chance produces a median gap this big. Just run this one (a 0 here means “smaller than 1000 shuffles can measure,” not zero):











Companion to the main lesson. Real data: a randomized stem-cell trial in sheep (Menasché et al., via the openintro R package).
